thread.title: MSU volleyball trips Terps, wins third straight Big Ten match

title: MSU volleyball trips Terps, wins third straight Big Ten match
text:
MSU volleyball trips Terps, wins third straight Big Ten match Lansing State Journal 10:08 a.m. EDT October 15, 2015 Coach Cathy George notches 200th victory MSU's Allyssah Fitterer (Photo: MSU Athletic Communications) 
EAST LANSING — Michigan State had four players with double-digit kills to down visiting Maryland, 3-1 (25-18, 22-25, 25-15, 25-18) on Wednesday night at Jenison Field House, giving coach Cathy George her 200th victory. 
The Spartans improve to 12-6 overall and won their second straight Big Ten match to improve to 4-3 in Conference play. 
The Terrapins remain winless in Big Ten play and fall below .500 at 10-11 overall. 
"We made things a little harder on ourselves than we maybe had to at times tonight, but we knew how scrappy and determined that Maryland was going to be coming in here," George said. "We had some small letdowns that gave Maryland some confidence, and they made us pay the price. I thought our middles were really good tonight, but we still need to work on being consistent and bringing the energy from the very beginning. It will certainly be a focus for us as we turn our attention to Rutgers." 
MSU hosts the Scarlet Knights at 7 p.m. Saturday at Jenison Field House. 
Top performers 
- Allyssah Fitterer had her best statistical performance since the opening weekend of the season, credited with 16 kills, hitting .500 (13-1-24), and a recording a season-best eight blocks. 
- Holly Toliver had her second double-double inside of a week, posting 11 kills, 10 digs and a block. 
- Rachel Minarick just missed a double-double with 46 assists, and added nine digs and three kills, and tying her season high with four blocks. 
- Alyssa Garvelink hit a team-best .529, comiling 11 digs and adding four blocks. 
- Chloe Reinig hit .346, her best since returning from injury. She had five of her 12 kills in the fifth set, and also added a season-best four blocks and three digs. 
- Abby Monson led all players with 16 digs, while Kristen Muir added 13, tying her best in a Big Ten match this season.
